    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-14T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-14T07:00:00-05:00" n="1370"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1370">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">103.9169 Asunción: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Paraguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reed</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Asunción</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-14T08:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 14, 1944—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 22—1 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–245. For Crowley and Zopf,<note n="14" xml:id="d1370fn14">Homer Zopf, Chief,
                        River Plate Division of the Foreign Economic Administration.</note> FEA.
                    Reference airgram A–170, June 5, 1944, 5:10 p.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d1370fn15"
                        >Not printed.</note> Export restrictions imposed by Argentina do not seem to
                    be working dangerous hardship on Paraguay’s economy so far but are resulting
                    mainly in annoying delays and lengthy negotiations between commercial houses and
                    licensing authorities in Argentina. An appreciable volume of essential goods is
                    entering this country from Argentina in the clandestine trade.</p>
                <p>The Embassy recommends no increases or additions to estimates of supply for this
                    country at present but is keeping in close touch with the situation in order to
                    inform the Department and FEA if any increased allocations are needed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
